  "prompt": "Are ductile metals also malleable?",
  "response": "Yes, ductile metals are generally also malleable, though these terms describe different properties. Ductility refers to a metal's ability to be stretched into a wire without breaking. Malleability, on the other hand, refers to a metal's ability to be hammered or rolled into thin sheets. Both ductility and malleability are characteristics of metals that display plasticity, allowing them to deform without fracturing under tensile or compressive stress, respectively. Many metals, like gold, silver, and copper, exhibit both ductility and malleability, making them versatile for various industrial and artistic applications.",
